\dropcap{R}ates of plant mortality are known to be highly variable among individuals, among coexisting species, between forests and from year-to-year [refs]. This variation has considerable consequences for forest structure and dynamics. Death of a single large tree can transfer up to 20000 kg of carbon from live-to-decaying carbon pools (Chave et al 200X), while at the same time opening up a gap that restarts a successional race, during which 10's-100's more plants may die while competing for a spot in the sun. In models of forest dynamics, variation in mortality rates has been found to have a larger impact on forest structure than absolute growth rates \cite{Johnson-2016}. As such, improving our ability to understand the mortality process is therefore a priority for making skilful predictions about forest dynamics and carbon, water or nutrient cycles; especially in an era of rapid environmental change.

Two substantial challenges exist when studying tree mortality in tropical rainforests. The first is that large population sizes and long periods of observation are required to make inferences into how various factors affect mortality rates. This requirement arises in part because the observable outcome -- alive vs. dead -- is one-step removed from the variable we ideally want to measure: $\lambda_i(t)$, the instantaneous rate of mortality for individual $i$ at time $t$ (also called a hazard rate). In classic survival analysis \cite{Kleinbaum:2012tn}, the probability that an individual dies between times $t_2$ and $t_3$ is expressed as a function of $\lambda_i(t)$:
\begin{equation} \label{eq:mortality_model}
p_{i,t_2\rightarrow t_3} = 1 - \exp\left(- \int_{t_2}^{t_3} \lambda_i(t) {\rm d}t\right).
\end{equation}
Here $\int_{t_2}^{t_3} \lambda_i(t) {\rm d}t$ is the ``cumulative hazard'' between $t_2$ and $t_3$ \cite{Kleinbaum:2012tn}. The observed survival outcome $S_{i, t_2\rightarrow t_3}$ (0 = alive, 1 = died) is then a realisation of this probability
\begin{equation}
S_{i,t_2\rightarrow t_3} \sim \textrm{Bernoulli}(p_{i,t_2\rightarrow t_3}).
\end{equation}
Since trees are generally long-lived, and because we are trying to estimate the shape of a continuous function from binary data, large sample-sizes are required. As such, detailed studies of forest tree mortality have only recently become possible, with the accumulation of growth and survival data from repeat surveys in long-term monitoring plots containining thousands of individuals and spanning several decades \cite{Anderson-Teixeira-2015a}.

The other major challenge when studying mortality -- similar to that faced in other fields like medicine and engineering -- is to derive suitable shapes for the underlying instantaneous mortality (hazard) function that accurately reflect observed patterns in mortality. Past research has identified a range of factors with significant effects on tree survival, including an individual's growth rate, traits, and size (XX). Generally, however, these influences have not been formalised as hazard functions (XX). Yet such functions are critical for forecasting temporal patterns in tree mortality, and consequently, changes in ecosystem function (XX). This is because hazard functions explicitly define the instantaneous rate of death per unit time and consequently provide vital information on when a death is likely to occur and how various covariates affect this.

A particular challenge is to integrate the observed conflicting relationships between mortality and growth observed within and across species. Within species, mortality rates tend to decrease for faster growing individuals, presumably because those individuals have superior carbon budgets and are thus better able to tolerate or repair diverse stresses \cite{Kobe:1995tw, Hawkes:2000ib, Keane:2001db}. Empirical studies provide broad support, with many highlighting non-linear declines in mortality with increased growth \cite[e.g.][]{Kobe:1997vy, Wyckoff:2002ul,Vieilledent:2010fv}. Yet across species, there tends to be a strong trade-off between growth and survival, with individuals from faster growing species having higher mortality than individuals from slower growing species \cite{Poorter:2008iu, Wright:2010fl}. This trade-off may arise via traits with antagonistic effects, such as wood density (biomass per unit wood volume). Denser wood -- which is more expensive to build and thus slows growth rates -- conveys enhanced physical strength, reduced stem breakage \cite{Putz:1983wu,vanGelder:2006exa,Chave:2009iy}, embolism \cite{Hacke:2001kj, Jacobsen:2005fx}, fungal or pathogen attack \cite{Augspurger:1984wx}, and ultimately reduced mortality \cite{Poorter:2008iu, Chave:2009iy, Kraft:2010kq, Wright:2010fl}.

