\subsection*{Growth hazard functions}
We found that the hazard function that incorporates both growth-dependent and baseline hazard terms (i.e. $(\alpha e^{\beta X_{i}} + \gamma)\delta$) and used stem diameter growth rather than basal-area growth, significantly outperformed both the baseline only (i.e.$\gamma \delta$) or growth-dependent only (i.e. $(\alpha e^{\beta X_{i}})\delta$) hazard functions (Fig. \ref{fig2}A). Surprisingly, we found that the growth-dependent only function did not improve predictive capacity over the baseline only function. Furthermore, we found that while the hazard function that incorporates both baseline and growth-dependent terms significantly improved model accuracy, this was only apparent if dbh growth was used.

