\subsection*{Effect of wood density on mortality rates}
The inclusion of wood density on either baseline or growth-dependent parameters significantly improved model accuracy relative to a hazard function without such effects (Fig. \ref{fig2} A,B). The most parsimonious combination that provided the largest gain in predictive accuracy (i.e. lowest logarithmic loss) occurred when only the baseline hazard term ($\gamma$) was varied as a function of species wood density ($\rho$; Fig. \ref{fig2} B). We found that wood density was negatively correlated with species baseline mortality rate (Fig. \ref{fig3}). This meant that species with low wood density had on average higher growth-independent mortality rates ((Fig. \ref{fig4} A,B), and thus higher annual probability of death (Fig. \ref{fig4} C,D), relative to high wood density species. While, wood density did improve model accuracy it only accounted for XX\% of the total gain in predictive capacity that could be obtained by accounting for species differences.

