\subsection*{Mortality rates, species light requirements and species maximum dbh}
We found that both $\alpha$, the effect of low growth rate, and $\gamma$, the baseline hazard term, were positively correlated with gap index (our measure of species light requirement; Fig. \ref{fig6} A,C, E). By contrast, $\beta$ (the parameter that defines the exponential decay with increasing growth rate) was negatively correlated gap index. The combination of these correlations suggest that species that predominately recruit in gaps (i.e. higher gap index) were more prone to death due to both low growth stochastic chance and required faster growth rates for a given mortality rate relative to a species that readily recruits in non-gaps. We detected no strong correlations between estimated species parameters and their associated maximum DBH (Fig. \ref{fig6} B,D,F,H).


